RAYMOND CLARK WAS BORN IN THE 1950S.
HE GREW UP LIVING IN A LIBRARY.
HE WAS ASHAMED OF HIS HOME, THE LIBRARY, AND DID NOT INVITE FRIENDS FROM SCHOOL OVER TO HIS HOME.
HE THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS RICH DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF BOOKS THEY HAD.
HE WOULD BE QUIET DURING THE DAY WHILE THE LIBRARY WAS OPEN FOR GUESTS AND PATRONS.
BUT AT NIGHT, HE WOULD RUN AROUND AND COULD BE AS LOUD AS HE WANTED TO BE.
HE WOULD READ BOOKS ALL THE TIME.
HE WAS IN THE CLEANING CREW.
HE PICKED UP TRASH FROM THE FLOOR.
HE ALSO WAXED THE TOP OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
YOU COULD SEE THE SHINING SHELF TOPS AS YOU WENT UP THE STAIRS.
HE WAS ABLE TO LIVE IN THE LIBRARY WITH HIS FAMILY DUE TO HIS JOB AT THE TIME.
CLARK LOVED READING, AS IT EXPANDED HIS THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE.
HE BECAME A TEACHER AT A UNIVERSITY SHORTLY AFTER.
HE HAD A NAME PLAQUE, SAYING "PROFESSOR CLARK", ON HIS DOOR.
HIS FATHER WAS VERY PROUD OF HIM.

RAYMOND CLARK GREW UP IN THE 1950S.
HIS FATHER WORKED IN A LIBRARY AS A CUSTODIAN.
CLARK BELIEVED THAT HIS FAMILY WAS POOR.
HIS SON SAID THEY WERE RICH.
THE SON DID NOT WANT TO INVITE FRIENDS FROM SCHOOL OVER .
HE WAS EMBARRASSED ABOUT LIVING IN A LIBRARY.
HE WAS ABLE TO RUN AROUND AND BE AS LOUD AS HE WANTED TO BE WHILE THE LIBRARY WAS CLOSED.
DURING HOURS, HOWEVER, HE HAD TO BE QUIET.
HIS READING ENABLED HIS THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE.
THE MOST REMARKABLE THING HE DID WAS WAX THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
HIS SON WENT THE FURTHEST IN HIS COLLEGIATE CAREER THAN ANY PREVIOUS RELATIVE.
HE GRADUATED AND BECAME A PROFESSOR.
HIS FATHER SAW THE NAME TAG SAYING PROFESSOR CLARK ON THE DOOR OF HIS SON'S CLASSROOM AND WAS QUIETLY HAPPY.
